{"query": "When planting non-crop vegetation to enhance natural pest control, what is the comparative evidence for planting new hedges versus plants that attract natural enemies with chemicals?", "summary": "For growing non-crop plants that produce chemicals that attract natural enemies, four studies from China, Germany, India and Kenya tested this approach (Action 724). Three studies found higher numbers of natural enemies in plots with plants that produce attractive chemicals, with all four studies finding a decrease in either pest population or pest damage. One replicated, randomised, controlled study found an increase in crop yield in plots with plants that produce attractive chemicals (Action 724). Studies tested this approach on lettuce, orange, safflower and sorghum crops (Action 724).

For planting new hedges, evidence shows more mixed results (Action 752). One randomised, replicated, controlled study from China found no effect on spiders in crops when comparing plots with and without hedges. Studies from France and China found varying effects - one found more natural enemies in hedges than in adjacent crops while another found this effect varied between crop types, hedge species and years. Two randomised, replicated, controlled studies from France and Kenya found natural enemy abundance in hedges was affected by the type of hedge shrub/tree planted, with effects varying between natural enemy groups (Action 752). For pest control, one study from Kenya found effects on nematodes varied between different nematode groups (Action 752). Crops studied for hedge interventions were barley, beans, maize and wheat (Action 752).

Additional evidence from France and the UK showed newly planted hedges had higher abundance, species richness or diversity of beetles or spiders than crop fields or field margins, with a literature review finding lower pest outbreaks in areas with new hedges (Action 538). However, effectiveness varied between different hedge plant species (Action 538).", "action_ids": ["724","752","538"]}

